The editors present this collection as a response to two conceptual deficiencies that characterize U.S.-Southwest approaches to the study of prehistory. The first is the "San Juan Hypothesis" initially championed by A.V. Kidder that supports an isolationist stance as regards in situ evo­lution of cultures located around the San Juan drainage. The second is the emphasis placed on ecological adapta­tionist models for change as a means of further straight­jacketing the Southwestern closed system. In contrast, Curtis Schaafsma and Carroll Riley present Casas Grandes regional culture as a "conduit" between the Anasazi and points south. Cultural interaction plays the dominant role as a source of change, particularly after A.D. 1250, when there is significant input from Mesoarnerica. 
In spite of its title, world systems approaches are refreshingly absent or downplayed in this collection of 17 papers. There is a marked return to the classic concept of the interaction sphere as defined by Stuart Streuver in 1972. Conceptually, this notion structures the book, which is divided into five sections including the introduction and conclusion. The remaining three sections address The Core Area, The Outer Sphere, and The Larger View. 
The Core Area is described by papers focusing on Casas Grandes Regional Culture, from site-specific treatments of Paquime and Villa Ahumada to regional studies around Paquime and in the west central portion of the state of Chi­huahua. These papers provide valuable reports on field­work and data analysis. Paul and Suzanne Fish examine the Animas phase (A.D. 1150-1350) occupations of the International Four Comers area on the northwest periph­ery of the Casas Grandes system. David Wilcox provides an engaging study of Paquime site structure and spatial organization using graph theory and access relationships. Finally, Steve Lekson comments on the overall affinity of Paquime for the general Puebloan culture-pattern, vis-a­vis Mesoamerica. These papers reveal a sociocultural com­plexity that only can be observed through recent regional studies and the expanded visionary scope of U.S., Cana­dian, and Mexican archaeologists across the Rio Grande. In the Outer Sphere, two papers describe the transition from Classic Mimbres to the Black Mountain phase in the twelfth century and the role of Casas Grandes in this tran­sition. A third paper provides a comprehensive presenta­tion on the site of Cerro de Trincheras in Sonora. The influence of Casas Grandes on the Outer Sphere is greatly diminished as compared to previously published estima­tions by Di Peso and others. These papers, however, only cover a portion of the intended region. As illustrated by Schaafsma's map of the Casa Grandes interaction sphere, ca. A.D. 1200--1425 (Figure 1), areas not discussed include a major portion of the mountains and eastern foothills of the northern Sierra Madre Occidental. Published work in this area is rare. Nevertheless, a review of current knowl­edge of Sierra sites including those described and/or exca­
vated by Carl Lumholtz, Robert Lister, Eduardo Gamboa, and Arturo Guevara Sanchez would have supported Schaafsma's reconfiguration and map of the Casas Grandes culture area. 
The Larger View presents a series of papers on the role of Casas Grandes Culture as a link between the Puebloan and Mesoarnerican worlds. Michael Foster presents the clearest description yet published on the Aztatlan Mer­cantile System and the role of Mesoarnerican influence in Medio Period florescence. The late Clement Meighan fur­ther supports arguments for contact in his description of shared resemblances between Hohokarn and the prehis­toric cultures of the West Coast of Mexico. Polly Schaaf­sma reviews evidence relating the Katchina Cult to Mesoamerican beliefs centering on water, earth, and Tlaloc. Finally, Alice Kehoe examines the issue of Casas Grandes cultural ties north of the Gulf of Mexico finding that coastal connections were more direct and substantial than any that Paquime could have sustained from the desert interior. The remaining papers examine the nature of the relationship of population and trade in northern Mexico and the U.S.-Southwest. This includes a consideration of Sonoran statelets by Carroll Riley as intermediaries for shell trade and as potential successors to post-Casas Grandes hegemony. Ronna Bradley provides a compre­hensive statistical study of shell trade identifying Casas Grandes as a supplier to the Mogollon, Western Pueblo, and late Anasazi. Finally in a brief essay, Christy Turner presents the results of his study of tooth crown morphol­ogy as an indicator of affinities between Mimbres, Sinaloa, and Casas Grandes populations. 
This final set of papers and the concluding statement by Schaafsma and Riley indicate that Charles Di Peso's mercantile model to explain the florescence of Casas Grandes Culture is no longer adequate. However, short of discarding the defining work on North Mexican prehis­tory, it is clear that new interpretations rely on what has come before. There is now a multiplicity of voices and lenses to accommodate the variety of approaches and data used to explain the past. These approaches range from studies of material culture to analyses of symbols and "fun­damental metaphors" that emphasize content over form in the archaeological record. 
The Casas Grandes World introduces a variety of new perspectives to understanding both a site and a culture. In combination with current work in Mexico and at Paquime under its new guise as a World Heritage Site, Casas Grandes archaeologists are redefining their own intellec­tual identity. In so doing, they transcend the current polit­ical boundary that for a long time has left northern Mexico both betwixt and between. I look forward to future stud­ies that will move even further from the characterization of Casas Grandes culture as conduit to cultural center in its own right. 
